Professor Nesbitt said that he realised very quickly what he had found.

‘Sometimes you know instantly if it's new and within about 30 seconds of picking up this bone I knew it was a new species.

‘I had hoped to find a leg bone to identify it, and I thought, “this is exactly why we're here” and I looked down and there were bones everywhere.

‘It turns out I was standing on bones that had been weathering out of the rock for hundreds of years - and it was all one individual of a new species.’

The reptile was recorded in the Journal of Vertebrate Palaeontology.

